issue.title: timeshift-gtk unnecessarily waits too much when creating or removing btrfs backup successfully
issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
timeshift-gtk unnecessarily waits too much when creating or removing btrfs backup successfully (even after the backup is done making or removing)

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behavior:
1. Go to timeshift-gtk
2. Click on Create Backup
3. Backup creates but you wait something like 20 more seconds unnecessarily

**Expected behavior**
Wait time shouldn't be that long after successful creation or removal.

**Screenshots**

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/f684f2a4-5cef-4c26-8687-1f8dd2e42ba6)

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/6ce59a82-1927-4a9f-9d06-012b4f270da8)

(15 or so seconds after successful creation)
![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2b5bfb02-60ad-4c05-8d24-0d7e973db5a2)

(15 or so seconds after successful removal)
![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/35ed32ca-48bc-47a0-ad06-0d3e2947ca89)

**System:**
 - Linux Distribution Name and Version: [Ubuntu Plucky]

issue.title: `cargo publish` stripping `hints` section from Cargo.toml

labels.name: S-triage
labels.description: Status: This issue is waiting on initial triage.

issue.body:
### Problem

We recently added `hints.mostly-unused = true` to several of the aws-sdk-rust crates to improve compilation time (ex: [aws-sdk-ec2](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-sdk-rust/blob/4fcc47b2babc2d3c78c9e7861d75328a6315fba5/sdk/ec2/Cargo.toml#L146-L147)). A [user reported](https://github.com/awslabs/aws-sdk-rust/issues/113#issuecomment-3182336182) that compiling with the new `-Zprofile-hint-mostly-unused` option did not improve their compilation times and that they did not see a `hints` section when looking at the crate in the Cargo cache. 

When looking at the [published source](https://docs.rs/crate/aws-sdk-ec2/1.158.0/source/Cargo.toml#149) on docs.rs (which I assume is the same as that on crates.io?) I also do not see a `hints` section. Running `cargo publish --dry-run` and looking at the generated package in `target/package` I can confirm that the `hints` section is removed from the package by the publish command.

Running `cargo +nightly publish --dry-run` does include the `hints` section in Cargo.toml 

### Steps

```sh
git clone --depth 1 https://github.com/awslabs/aws-sdk-rust.git;
cd aws-sdk-rust/sdk/ec2;

# Finds hints
cat Cargo.toml | grep hints;

# If you add +nightly here all works as expected
cargo publish --dry-run;

# Does not find hints (unless you add +nightly in the line above)
cat ../../target/package/aws-sdk-ec2-1.158.0/Cargo.toml | grep hints;
```

### Possible Solution(s)

I suspect that `cargo publish` is stripping out unrecognized sections in Cargo.toml, and we are not publishing with nightly and the `-Zprofile-hint-mostly-unused` option. This should likely be more permissive in allowing sections through. 

### Notes

_No response_

### Version

```sh
# Local testing
$ cargo --version
cargo 1.89.0 (c24e10642 2025-06-23)

$ cargo +nightly --version
cargo 1.91.0-nightly (840b83a10 2025-07-30)


# Actual publishing
$ cargo --version
cargo 1.86.0 (adf9b6ad1 2025-02-28)
```

issue.title: tests: make uio test regex work with musl
issue.body:
musl-libc handles the `pwrite` calls differently than glibc, making the uio tests fail. Using glibc, there are separated `pwrite` and `pwritev` calls, however musl uses only `pwritev2` for both `pwrite` and `pwritev`.

To account to this difference, change the verifying regex in way to match both glibc and musl outputs.

Closes #346

Home Assistant

pull_request.title: 288: Implement Multivariate scoring - WIP
pull_request.body:
<!-- Thanks for opening this pull request! Below we have provided a suggested template for PRs to this repository and a checklist to complete before opening a PR -->
 
## Description

(marked as WIP because there are open items, but would still like to get some feedback on the basic functionality)

This PR closes #288.

This PR represents a first draft for introducing multivariate scoring to `scoringutils`. 

It extends `score.forecast_sample()` to handle multivariate forecasts. It also adds a new form of possible metrics, multivariate metrics, which accept a `grouping_id` argument. The workflow is outlined in a [new Vignette](https://github.com/epiforecasts/scoringutils/blob/multivariate/vignettes/scoring-multivariate-forecasts.Rmd). 

`score.forecast_sample()` handles the data-wrangling as before. It transforms the data to a big matrix where rows represent observations/forecasts and columns represent samples. The difference between uni- and multivariate forecasts is now that several rows get grouped to a single multivariate forecasts. This gets handled by the scoring metric, which applies the score to the matrix according to the grouping specified in `grouping_id`. 

For the `data.table` part, grouping is defined in terms of column names, just as with the forecast unit. There is a function to set and get the grouping. A "grouped" forecast is a normal forecast that just has an additional special grouping column. 


Open issues: 
- still need to add a `set_grouping` argument to `as_forecast_sample()`
- PR needs unit tests
- slightly undecided whether we should name it "grouping" or "group" everywhere
- I can see that it would be more convenient to define grouping as the names of the columns over which you'd like to group. For example, you might want to group over locations, or horizons. The way it currently works is essentially by specifying the grouping elements analogously to the forecast unit.
